  "prompt": "Why are newspapers like The Economic Times, Financial Times and others printed on pink paper?",
  "response": "The practice of printing certain financial newspapers on pink paper, such as The Economic Times and the Financial Times, serves several purposes:\n\n1. **Tradition**: The use of pink paper dates back to the 19th century and has become a distinct characteristic of financial newspapers. The Financial Times, established in 1888, adopted pink paper to differentiate itself from other publications, and this tradition has continued.\n\n2. **Visibility**: The bright color helps the newspapers stand out on newsstands, making them easily identifiable among other publications. This distinctiveness can attract readers who associate the color with financial news.\n\n3. **Branding**: The unique color serves as a branding tool. Readers around the world associate pink paper with serious financial news and analysis, reinforcing the identity of these publications in the media landscape.\n\n4. **Historical Context**: The specific shade of pink used by the Financial Times, known as \"FT Pink,\" has become symbolic of quality journalism in finance. This historical context contributes to the newspaper's prestige and recognition.\n\nOverall, the use of pink paper in financial newspapers has become a blend of tradition, branding, and functionality in helping readers identify these publications quickly.",
